value.value: Specialized epithelial cells involved in the maintenance of osmotic homeostasis. They are characterized by abundant mitochondria and ion transporters. In amniotes, they are present in the renal system. In freshwater fish, ionocytes in the skin and gills help maintain osmotic homeostasis by absorbing salt from the external environment.
Kolmer-Agduhr neurons are ciliated GABAergic neurons that contact the central canal of the spinal cord and have ipsilateral ascending axons.
An auditory hair cell located in the macula that is sensitive to auditory stimuli.

A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney which regulates sodium and potassium balance. The activity of sodium and potassium channels on the apical membrane of the cell is regulated by aldosterone and vasopressin. In mammals this cell type is located in the renal collecting duct system.
A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney that regulates acid/base balance.

Intercalated cells are also called “mitochondria-rich cells”, reflecting the high levels of round mitochondria at their apical pole, or in their cytoplasm, a distribution that is quite different from that of other kidney tubule cells, which accumulated mitochondria around the basolateral membrane. These cells also have numerous irregular apical microvilli compared with the surrounding segment-specific cells. Intercalated cells lack a central cilium, at least in the cortex, which also differentiates them from the adjacent principal cells.
A cuboidal epithelial cell of the kidney which secretes acid and reabsorbs base to regulate acid/base balance.
Type A intercalated cells are the more abundant type of intercalated cell in the outer stripe of the outer medulla in most mammalian species.
A ciliated epithelial cell with many cilia.
A ciliated epithelial cell with a single cilium.
A non-sensory cell that extends from the basement membrane to the apical surface of the auditory epithelium and provides support for auditory hair cells.
An auditory epithelial support cell that surrounds the nerve fibers and synapses of the auditory inner hair cells.
A cell that secretes ghrelin, the peptide hormone that stimulates hunger.
Ghrelin secreting cells found in the endocrine pancreas.

definition.value: In mammals the endocrine pancreas is called the Islets of Langerhans.

value.value: Lymphatic progenitor cells.
Mesenchymal derived lymphatic progenitor cells that give rise to the superficial lymphatics.
Lymphatic progenitor cells, derived from the veins, that give rise to lymphatic endothelial cells.
Cranial motor neuron which innervates muscles derived from the branchial (pharyngeal) arches.
A motor neuron that innervates a skeletal muscle.  These motor neurons are all excitatory and cholinergic.
A motor neuron that synapses to parasympathetic neurons that innervate tear glands, sweat glands, and the smooth muscles and glands of the pulmonary, cardiovascular, and gastrointestinal systems.

definition.value: Note that these neurons do not synapse directly onto muscles

value.value: Multi fate stem cell that gives rise to both hepatocytes and cholangiocytes as descendants. The term often refers to fetal precursors of hepatocytes (differently from 'hepatic stem cell', usually applied to the self-renewing pool of hepatocyte precursors in the adult liver). Hepatoblasts may also be endogenous, as some stem cells found in the liver come from the bone marrow via blood circulation.

Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into an ameloblast. Located in the inner enamel epithelium, these cells elongate, their nuclei shift distally (away from the dental papilla), and their cytoplasm becomes filled with organelles needed for synthesis and secretion of enamel proteins.

definition.value: unsure of neural crest contribution. In VSAO we have develops_from CL:0000008

value.value: Cell that has the potential to form a skeletal cell type (e.g. cells in periosteum, cells in marrow) and produce extracellular matrix (often mineralized) and skeletal tissue (often mineralized).

definition.value: Needs logical definition. Should be capable_of skeletal system morphogenesis? or skeletal tissue development? needs to be added to GO. NOTES:a cell type of the early embryo (see also: mesenchymal cells) that will give rise to mineralized connective tissue. Scleroblasts can differentiate into osteoblasts (bone-forming cells), chondroblasts (cartilage-forming cells), odontoblasts (dentin-forming cells), ameloblasts (enamel-forming cells). The mesenchymal cells developing into osteoblasts and chondroblasts are derived from the mesoderm. Those developing into odontoblasts are neural crest cells. Those developing into ameloblasts are derived from the ectoderm. (http://www.copewithcytokines.de/cope.cgi?key=scleroblasts)

value.value: Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a cementoblast.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to form an odontoblast, deposits predentine, and arises from a cranial neural crest cell.
Cell that is part of the neural crest region of the neuroepithelium, prior to migration. Note that not all premigratory neural crest cells may become migratory neural crest cells.
Cell that is part of the notochord.

definition.value: NOTE: TO DO, notochord development still needs work.

value.value: Mesodermal cell that is axially located and gives rise to the cells of the notochord.
Notochordal cell that is part of the outer epithelium of the notochord and surrounds the vacuolated notochord cells.
Notochordal cell that is inner portion of the notochord and becomes vacuolated as development proceeds.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to develop into a chondroblast; and arises from neural crest, meseosdermal and notochordal and connective tissue cells.
Skeletogenic cell that has the potential to transform into an osteoblast, and develops from neural crest or mesodermal cells.
Neuron that is part of the enteric nervous system.
Odontoblast that non-terminally differentiated, located in the odontogenic papilla and dentine tissue, and transforms from a odontoblast cell.
Odontoblast that is terminally differentiated and derived from an odontogenic papilla and associated with dentine.
Muscle precursor cell that is adjacent to the notochord and part of the presomitic mesoderm.

definition.value: In teleosts, adaxial cells give rise to slow muscle myoblasts.

value.value: An epidermal cell with apical microvilli or a single apical projection have synaptic associations with nerve fibres in the epidermis.

definition.value: Taxon specificity not yet fully known, but are known in anuran larvae but not in adults.

value.value: Ciliated cell of the embryonic epidermis and functions in embryonic movements.

definition.value: Taxon specificity not clear -present in embryonic anurans.
taxon specificity not clear. Appears in early larval stages of anurans and persists after metamorphosis.

value.value: Characteristic early embryonic cell with a bottle or flask shape that is first to migrate inwards at the blastopore during gastrulation in amphibians.

Secretory cell that produces a chemical mixture that triggers antipredator behavior. The substance is released only upon disruption of the epidermis. [Behavior of teleost fishes, second edition, edited by Pitcher, 1992]

A specialized pore forming cell of the follicle, located adjacent to the animal pole of the oocyte. The micropylar cell makes the single micropyle (pore) through the chorion through which the sperm fertilizes the egg.
Epidermal cell rich in mitochondria. In amphibians, appears during metamorphosis.
Any muscle cell in which the fibers are not organised into sarcomeres.
Any hematopoietic cell that is a precursor of some other hematopoietic cell type.
A transversely striated, synctial cell of skeletal muscle. It is formed when proliferating myoblasts exit the cell cycle, differentiate and fuse.
A myotube that is part of some somatic muscle.  Examples include arthropod somatic muscle cells.
A muscle cell that is part of some somatic muscle.
A somatic muscle cell that is oblquely striated.  Examples include the somatic muscles of nematodes.

A myoblast that detemines the properties (size, shape and attachment to the epidermis) of a `somatic muscle myotube` (CL:0008003) .  It develops into a somatic muscle myotube via fusion with `fusion component myoblasts` (CL:0000621).
A muscle cell that is part of some visceral muscle.
A visceral muscle cell that is striated.  Examples include the visceral muscle cells of arhtropods.
